div.p: To James McCulloch
V70/6999, unit 467, VPRS 3991/P inward registered correspondence, VA 475 Chief Secretary's Department, Public Record Office, Victoria.

MS written by Georg Luehmann and signed and addressed by M.
Melbourne Botanic Garden
23rd June 1870
Sir

In accordance with your instructions I have now the honor to transmit the returns required by Parliament in reference to the expenditure of the Botanic Garden during my administration, and the records of the property accumulated during my directorship.
The file includes an extract from the Votes and Proceedings of the Legislative Assembly, Wednesday 25th May 1870, prepared by the Clerk of the Assembly, John Martin:
5. Botanical Gardens . Mr Everard moved, pursuant to amended notice, That there be laid upon the Table of the House a Return showing:—
(1.) The cost of the Botanical Gardens during the management of Dr Mueller.
(2.) The Public Institutions that have received plants from the Gardens during the same period.
(3.) The number and value of such plants, and the number and value of plants given to private individuals.
(4.) The present estimated value of plants at present in the Nurseries of the Botanical Gardens.
(5.) The value of permanent improvements.
Question — put and resolved in the affermative.
M's letter was accompanied by the Return that follows; the file cover has a note by the Under Secretary, W. Odgers: 'Return sent to Clerk L. Assembly 7.7.70'. The file includes a separate page in M's hand that was evidently intended to serve as the heading for the Return: 'Return of the expenditure of the botanic Garden and the scientific institutions connected therewith from 1857 til June 1870, also of the present property of the establishment. (Correspondence)'. The Return itself, accompanied b a copy of M's letter, is now located at No. 249, unit 304, VPRS 3253/P Original papers tabled in the Legislative Assembly, VA number, Public Record Office, Victoria. This is a parliament MS. We'll need their permission if we wish to publish because not covered by PRO. Also needs a letter of permission to access it for proofing

After a careful valuation the property of the Botanic Garden, inclusive of the value of the plants distributed to Public and Government Institutions or for industrial purposes, from 1857 till 1870 amounts to £98,287 — s d whereas the expenditure, exclusive of special zoological disbursements and the cost of the Yarra bridges, has been £92,903.17/—

The lasting information afforded and numberless services rendered by the establishment under my charge since that time must be regarded as an additional and gratuitous boon of the Government to the community here and to countries abroad.
